WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.160
Hi everyone, I'm Isabella Velazquez, and alongside Daniel Chen, we're going to walk

00:00:08.160 --> 00:00:11.760
through a demo of a Modern Marketing Mix Modeling workflow.

00:00:11.760 --> 00:00:17.240
We'll show you how to use Pawset tools to create an organized, reproducible pipeline

00:00:17.240 --> 00:00:21.680
that can help you distill your model results into clear, actionable insights that you can

00:00:21.680 --> 00:00:23.840
relate to your stakeholders.

00:00:23.840 --> 00:00:28.480
This workflow was inspired by the fantastic discussions with Ryan Timpe and the community

00:00:28.480 --> 00:00:33.279
at a recent Data Science Hangout, so thank you to everyone who sparked these ideas.

00:00:33.279 --> 00:00:38.439
Let's first quickly introduce Marketing Mix Modeling, or MMM.

00:00:38.439 --> 00:00:43.840
Rachel Dempsey and Mark Rieke shared a great metaphor for Marketing Mix Modeling, unbaking

00:00:43.840 --> 00:00:45.240
a cake.

00:00:45.240 --> 00:00:50.099
In marketing, we're often handed the cake, or the total revenue, and asked to figure

00:00:50.099 --> 00:00:56.040
out exactly which ingredients made it taste so good, and which ones were unnecessary.

00:00:56.599 --> 00:01:00.080
MMM does this by unbaking the cake.

00:01:00.080 --> 00:01:06.040
It identifies the impact of every ingredient—the flour, the sugar, or even the luck of the

00:01:06.040 --> 00:01:12.440
oven temperature—to answer these sorts of questions.

00:01:12.440 --> 00:01:20.000
More concretely, MMM is an analytical approach that uses statistical techniques on marketing

00:01:20.160 --> 00:01:27.400
time series data to estimate the impact of different marketing tactics on key performance

00:01:27.400 --> 00:01:29.480
metrics.

00:01:29.480 --> 00:01:37.559
Executing an MMM produces a sophisticated blend of technical metrics and strategic insights.

00:01:37.559 --> 00:01:44.160
On the technical side, it generates statistical outputs such as model coefficients, confidence

00:01:44.160 --> 00:01:47.919
intervals, and goodness-of-fit measures.

00:01:47.919 --> 00:01:54.199
On the strategic side, the model yields visual and actionable assets, including contribution

00:01:54.199 --> 00:02:02.080
waterfall charts, cross-channel return-on-ad-spend comparisons, and diminishing-return curves.

00:02:02.080 --> 00:02:09.360
By reviewing these outputs, stakeholders can solve critical business uncertainties, such

00:02:09.360 --> 00:02:16.960
as attribution, how many sales did a specific channel drive over the past year, predictive

00:02:16.960 --> 00:02:22.759
forecasting, such as how would total sales shift if I invested X amount of dollars into

00:02:22.759 --> 00:02:29.600
a specific channel next year, and optimization—what is the ideal budget allocation to maximize

00:02:29.600 --> 00:02:31.399
future revenue?

00:02:31.399 --> 00:02:37.399
Ultimately, these insights allow businesses to optimize their marketing investments and

00:02:37.399 --> 00:02:44.720
turn historical data into a roadmap for future growth.

00:02:44.759 --> 00:02:51.360
In an MMM, inputs are all marketing variables and factors, including media, like social

00:02:51.360 --> 00:02:58.720
or search, baseline factors, like seasonality or brand equity, and external factors, like

00:02:58.720 --> 00:03:01.919
the economy or even the weather.

00:03:01.919 --> 00:03:07.960
Outputs consist of business metrics and KPIs, such as sales revenue, market share, and customer

00:03:07.960 --> 00:03:08.960
acquisition.

00:03:08.960 --> 00:03:13.320
It's important to note that MMM is meant to be a holistic view.

00:03:13.839 --> 00:03:19.320
It's supposed to measure outcomes for all marketing channels together in one analysis.

00:03:19.320 --> 00:03:25.320
It uses aggregate data, not individual user information, and so is often considered a

00:03:25.320 --> 00:03:29.320
privacy-first approach.

00:03:29.320 --> 00:03:34.039
Just as there are dozens of brands of eggs, flour, and milk at the grocery store, there

00:03:34.039 --> 00:03:37.039
are many ways to bake an MMM.

00:03:37.039 --> 00:03:41.440
No two data science teams use the exact same ingredient.

00:03:41.559 --> 00:03:44.440
Within open source, there are many options.

00:03:44.440 --> 00:03:49.800
For Python, there are tools like Google's Meridian or PyMC Marketing.

00:03:49.800 --> 00:03:55.520
For R, there are tools like Meta's Robin or building custom high-flexibility workflows

00:03:55.520 --> 00:04:02.800
using tidy models and RStandarm, as Ryan Tsingpei detailed in his Posit 2023 talk.

00:04:02.800 --> 00:04:05.880
You also have to choose your style of baking.

00:04:05.880 --> 00:04:11.279
Are you using Bayesian methods to incorporate priors, which are marketing insights that

00:04:11.279 --> 00:04:17.000
can be included in the model, or a more traditional frequentist approach?

00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:21.480
But the best recipes in the world don't matter if your kitchen is a mess and your

00:04:21.480 --> 00:04:24.880
oven isn't calibrated.

00:04:24.880 --> 00:04:28.239
And this is where we propose Posit tools for the process.

00:04:28.239 --> 00:04:33.760
While the MMM workflow shares many steps with traditional data science, the stakes are high

00:04:33.760 --> 00:04:37.160
since you're justifying budget and resources.

00:04:37.160 --> 00:04:41.480
Posit tools can help you develop reproducible, transparent, and defensible models for your

00:04:41.480 --> 00:04:44.279
team with a code-first integrated approach.

00:04:44.279 --> 00:04:49.839
And with that, I'll pass it to Dan to show you this workflow starting in Positron, the

