00:09:41.640 --> 00:09:42.640
Now let's talk about MMMs.

00:09:42.640 --> 00:09:44.679
There's a few things that make MMMs special.

00:09:44.679 --> 00:09:47.359
There's a temporal time series component.

00:09:47.359 --> 00:09:52.960
There are carryover effects, meaning money spent now does not always mean immediate revenue,

00:09:52.960 --> 00:09:56.239
and there are diminishing returns where impact may decrease with spend.

00:09:56.239 --> 00:10:00.880
Here we'll fit two different models, a linear regression model and a weakly informative

00:10:00.880 --> 00:10:05.719
Bayesian linear regression model, and we'll fit these same models with the carryover and

00:10:05.719 --> 00:10:10.080
diminishing returns transformation for a total of four models.

00:10:10.080 --> 00:10:14.359
Because we're working in a professional IDE, we can track our experiments.

00:10:14.359 --> 00:10:18.960
If a model looks too good to be true, we can look back on the code and the parameters to

00:10:18.960 --> 00:10:27.119
see exactly why.

00:10:27.119 --> 00:10:31.520
One of the things TinyModels gives us is the ability to split our data into training and

00:10:31.520 --> 00:10:33.359
test sets.

00:10:33.359 --> 00:10:37.599
TinyModels also has a function that splits time series data into training and testing

00:10:37.760 --> 00:10:40.760
by keeping the temporal component of the data intact.

00:10:40.760 --> 00:10:50.559
Essentially, we'll train the first 80% of the data to test on the last 20%.

00:10:50.559 --> 00:10:53.640
Our linear regression model is using TinyModels.

00:10:53.640 --> 00:10:58.599
We set this up just like every other model in TinyModels, where we create a spec for

00:10:58.599 --> 00:11:04.440
the model, the recipe, add it to a workflow, and then we can fit our model.

00:11:04.440 --> 00:11:10.479
And then we go through this same training, testing, and look at some of our training

00:11:10.479 --> 00:11:13.760
metrics.

00:11:13.760 --> 00:11:18.239
Because this is linear regression, we can also go and extract our coefficients.

00:11:18.239 --> 00:11:26.159
These coefficients will play a role in the results for our MMM model.

00:11:26.159 --> 00:11:30.960
We can then write a function to calculate our addStock carryover effect.

00:11:30.960 --> 00:11:36.559
And then we can also go and calculate our saturation or diminishing returns function.

00:11:36.559 --> 00:11:43.159
Next, we can use regular tidyverse functions to take our existing training data and apply

00:11:43.159 --> 00:11:45.780
these transformations to it.

00:11:45.780 --> 00:11:51.320
These transform columns is one way where we do feature engineering for our MMM models.

00:11:51.320 --> 00:11:56.479
Lastly, we want to use our transformation functions, but to prevent data leakage, we

00:11:56.479 --> 00:12:00.760
want to make sure that we're transforming and carrying over the last value from our

00:12:00.760 --> 00:12:03.919
training data set into our testing data set.

00:12:03.919 --> 00:12:09.960
And then we go and use the tidyverse functions again, but this time on our test data.

00:12:09.960 --> 00:12:14.559
Then we go and perform our linear regression model just like before, but we use the data

00:12:14.559 --> 00:12:17.119
set with these transformations applied.

00:12:17.119 --> 00:12:20.479
Our response variable is still going to be sales revenue.

00:12:20.479 --> 00:12:24.880
For the last two models, we'll fit the same transformed and non-transformed data to a

00:12:24.880 --> 00:12:27.440
Bayesian linear regression model.

